<h1>Problem 2138 - 2022 IMOCSL, A2</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(x_1\), \(x_2\), \(\ldots\), \(x_{2025}\) be real numbers with \(x_1^2+x_2^2+\cdots+x_{2025}^2=1\). Determine the maximum value of \[|x_1-x_2|+|x_2-x_3|+\cdots +|x_{2024}-x_{2025}|+|x_{2025}-x_1|\]</p>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Upon an encounter with an expression in an inequality you want to “<i>termwise-square</i>”, think of QM-AM. I think Cauchy-Schwarz is also a thing (possibly isomorphic to this).<br><br>
The other main part of the problem is when you realise that odds are a little
inconvenient - the key idea there is to somehow <b>use the flaws to your advantage</b>
and <b>reduce to the already solved case</b>.</p>
